{
  "documentVersion": "1.1",
  "layout": {
    "pageSize": {
      "width": 600,
      "height": 800
    },
    "margins": {
      "top": 50,
      "right": 50,
      "bottom": 50,
      "left": 50
    },
    "fontFamily": "Arimo",
    "fontSize": 10,
    "lineHeight": 1.4,
    "pageBackground": "#fcfbf7"
  },
  "fonts": {
    "regular": "Arimo",
    "bold": "Arimo"
  },
  "styles": {
    "h1": {
      "fontSize": 24,
      "fontWeight": "bold",
      "marginBottom": 12,
      "keepWithNext": true,
      "color": "#233b56"
    },
    "h2": {
      "fontSize": 14,
      "fontWeight": "bold",
      "marginBottom": 8,
      "keepWithNext": true,
      "color": "#33577d"
    },
    "p": {
      "marginBottom": 8
    },
    "sidebar-label": {
      "fontSize": 9,
      "fontWeight": "bold",
      "marginBottom": 4,
      "color": "#555555"
    },
    "sidebar-body": {
      "fontSize": 9,
      "marginBottom": 6,
      "color": "#333333"
    }
  },
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": "Zone Map: Placed Field Actors"
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "content": "This proof removes the embedded story and places visible exclusion-field actors directly inside the zone. Later ordinary zone children should walk around those placed bodies the way map labels or notes would skirt rocks."
    },
    {
      "type": "zone-map",
      "properties": {
        "style": {
          "marginTop": 12,
          "marginBottom": 12
        }
      },
      "zones": [
        {
          "id": "main",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "h2",
              "content": "Main Zone"
            },
            {
              "type": "field-actor",
              "content": "",
              "properties": {
                "spatialField": {
                  "kind": "exclude",
                  "x": 20,
                  "y": 52,
                  "wrap": "around",
                  "gap": 6,
                  "exclusionAssembly": {
                    "members": [
                      { "shape": "circle", "x": 0, "y": 38, "w": 64, "h": 64 },
                      { "shape": "rect", "x": 40, "y": 48, "w": 74, "h": 24 },
                      { "shape": "circle", "x": 86, "y": 8, "w": 78, "h": 78 },
                      { "shape": "circle", "x": 132, "y": 58, "w": 34, "h": 34 }
                    ]
                  }
                },
                "style": {
                  "width": 168,
                  "backgroundColor": "#f8f6ef",
                  "height": 110
                }
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "field-actor",
              "content": "",
              "properties": {
                "spatialField": {
                  "kind": "exclude",
                  "x": 176,
                  "y": 150,
                  "wrap": "around",
                  "gap": 6,
                  "exclusionAssembly": {
                    "members": [
                      { "shape": "circle", "x": 10, "y": 0, "w": 58, "h": 58 },
                      { "shape": "circle", "x": 0, "y": 36, "w": 44, "h": 44 },
                      { "shape": "rect", "x": 28, "y": 34, "w": 58, "h": 20 },
                      { "shape": "circle", "x": 72, "y": 26, "w": 28, "h": 28 }
                    ]
                  }
                },
                "style": {
                  "width": 102,
                  "backgroundColor": "#f8f6ef",
                  "height": 84
                }
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "p",
              "content": "This label block should immediately choose a lane around the first placed rock rather than pretending the zone is a story."
            },
            {
              "type": "p",
              "content": "A later block should encounter a different free interval once the upper mass falls away and the second rock begins to matter."
            },
            {
              "type": "p",
              "content": "The interesting question is not whether the result looks like typography wrap, but whether ordinary zone actors appear to walk around explicit placed bodies inside the map."
            },
            {
              "type": "p",
              "content": "That is the more generic capability we care about: rocks, hazards, creatures, or invisible influence zones can all publish spatial fields while the host remains just a region."
            },
            {
              "type": "p",
              "content": "If this proof is honest, the circles in the assembly should also be visible in the rendered bodies now instead of disappearing into one rectangular proxy."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "sidebar",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "sidebar-label",
              "content": "ZONE NOTE"
            },
            {
              "type": "sidebar-body",
              "content": "The sidebar still ignores the hidden field entirely. Native consumption stays local to the main zone."
            },
            {
              "type": "sidebar-label",
              "content": "WHY IT MATTERS"
            },
            {
              "type": "sidebar-body",
              "content": "This proof shows a zone can host explicit placed field actors without first embedding a story."
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "zoneLayout": {
        "columns": [
          {
            "mode": "flex",
            "fr": 2
          },
          {
            "mode": "flex",
            "fr": 1
          }
        ],
        "gap": 16
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "content": "Content below the zone-map resumes in normal document flow after the native field actor proof."
    }
  ]
}
